---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro"
import TopicHero from "../components/TopicHero.astro"
import TopicNav from "../components/TopicNav.astro"
import Figure from "../components/Figure.astro"
import Gallery from "../components/Gallery.astro"

import g05 from "../assets/images/gallery-05.png"
import g09 from "../assets/images/gallery-09.png"
import reproHero from "../assets/images/repro-hero.png"

const cycle = [
  { label: "Breeding season", text: "A short window in late winter and early spring. Females are receptive for only a day or two, making timing critical." },
  { label: "Gestation", text: "Roughly 66–75 days, after which the female gives birth in a sheltered den, rock crevice, or borrowed burrow." },
  { label: "Litter size", text: "Typically 2–6 kittens, born blind and helpless with a darker, woolly coat that lightens as they mature." },
  { label: "Independence", text: "Kittens begin hunting at around 4 months and reach adult size by 6–8 months, dispersing to find their own range." },
]

const gallery = [
  { src: reproHero.src, alt: "Two Pallas's cat kittens at a den entrance", caption: "Litters shelter in dens until they are strong enough to follow the hunt." },
  { src: g09.src, alt: "A single Pallas's cat kitten exploring", caption: "Young manuls face steep odds in their first year." },
  { src: g05.src, alt: "A Pallas's cat resting curled among rocks", caption: "Adults are long-lived in captivity but face a far shorter span in the wild." },
]
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Reproduction & Lifespan — The Manul Atlas"
  description="Breeding season, vulnerable kittens, and the lifespan of the Pallas's cat in the wild and captivity."
  image={reproHero.src}
>
  <TopicHero
    eyebrow="Chapter 05 · Reproduction & Lifespan"
    title="A narrow window, a hard beginning"
    intro="The manul's brief breeding season and vulnerable young reflect the demands of raising a litter on one of the planet's most unforgiving landscapes."
    image={reproHero.src}
    imageAlt="Two fluffy Pallas's cat kittens peering from a rocky den"
  />

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-16 lg:px-0">
    <div class="prose-editorial">
      <p>
        Reproduction in the Pallas's cat is shaped by the steppe's short, harsh seasons. Mating occurs in a narrow
        window in late winter, around December to early spring depending on latitude. Females come into estrus only
        briefly — often a window of just a day or two — so males must locate and compete for receptive females
        quickly. This compressed timing helps ensure that kittens are born when spring brings milder weather and
        rising prey numbers.
      </p>
      <p>
        After a gestation of roughly 66 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of two to six kittens in a
        sheltered den. Newborns are blind, helpless, and covered in a darker, woolly coat. The mother raises them
        alone; as in most cats, the male plays no role in rearing young.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="my-12">
      <Figure
        src={g09.src}
        alt="A young Pallas's cat kitten exploring rocky ground"
        caption="Mortality in the first year is high. Harsh weather, predators such as eagles and foxes, and the difficulty of learning to hunt all take a heavy toll on young manuls."
        ratio="16/10"
      />
    </div>

    <h2 class="mb-6 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink">From den to dispersal</h2>
    <div class="grid gap-px overflow-hidden rounded-[var(--radius-card)] border border-line bg-line sm:grid-cols-2">
      {cycle.map((c) => (
        <div class="bg-parchment-2 p-6">
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-semibold text-ink">{c.label}</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-soft">{c.text}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <div class="prose-editorial mt-12">
      <h2 class="mb-4 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink">Lifespan</h2>
      <p>
        Kittens grow quickly. They begin venturing out and learning to hunt at around four months and approach
        adult size by six to eight months, after which they disperse to establish their own home ranges. Females
        can breed in their first year, an adaptation that helps offset high juvenile mortality.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the wild, life is short: many Pallas's cats live only a few years, with average wild lifespans estimated
        around six years given predation, disease, and the rigors of the climate. In captivity, where those
        pressures are removed, individuals can live to eleven or twelve years — though captive breeding remains
        challenging due to the species' sensitivity to stress and high infant susceptibility to disease.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-5 lg:px-8">
    <Gallery images={gallery} columns={3} />
  </section>

  <TopicNav current="/reproduction" />
  <div class="h-10"></div>
</BaseLayout>
